### wordShl() {#ad9b9b9053c292521a0ca484f3333bd6c}

<MemberDefinition
  prototype={<>void llvm::BitVector::wordShl (uint32&#95;t Count)</>}
  labels = {["inline"]}>
Perform a logical left shift of <code>Count</code> words by moving everything <code>Count</code> words to the right in memory.

While confusing, words are stored from least significant at Bits&#91;0&#93; to most significant at Bits&#91;NumWords-1&#93;. A logical shift left, however, moves the current least significant bit to a higher logical index, and fills the previous least significant bits with 0. Thus, we actually need to move the bytes of the memory to the right, not to the left. Example: Words = &#91;0xBBBBAAAA, 0xDDDDFFFF, 0x00000000, 0xDDDD0000&#93; represents a <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/bitvector">BitVector</a> where 0xBBBBAAAA contain the least significant bits. So if we want to shift the <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/bitvector">BitVector</a> left by 2 words, we need to turn this into 0x00000000 0x00000000 0xBBBBAAAA 0xDDDDFFFF by using a memmove which moves right, not left.

Definition at line <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/adt/bitvector-h/#l00744">744</a> of file <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/adt/bitvector-h">BitVector.h</a>.
</MemberDefinition>

### wordShr() {#a87571f841702b93e1c45472cb97c4c36}

<MemberDefinition
  prototype={<>void llvm::BitVector::wordShr (uint32&#95;t Count)</>}
  labels = {["inline"]}>
Perform a logical right shift of <code>Count</code> words by moving those words to the left in memory.

See wordShl for more information.

Definition at line <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/adt/bitvector-h/#l00762">762</a> of file <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/adt/bitvector-h">BitVector.h</a>.
